By using rnorm() we can create ideal normal distribution using the mean and standard deviation of the data.

data.norm=rnorm(1000,mean(data$Total.Cases,sd(data$Total.Cases)))
hist(data.norm, freq = FALSE)
lines(density(data.norm))

Quantile-Quantile Plot: It produces a series of points that appers in a straight line for normal distribution.

qqnorm(data$Total.Cases)# for non-normal distribution

qqnorm(data.norm)# for normal distribution

data.norm2=rnorm(1000,mean(data$Total.Deaths,sd(data$Total.Deaths)))

It is possible to plot one distribution against another as a quantile-quantile plot using the qqplot() command.

qqplot(data$Total.Cases, data$Total.Deaths)

qqplot(data.norm, data.norm2)

Drawing a straight line on the qqplot() can be done using the abline() command. This command uses the properties of a straight line (that is, y = a + bx) to produce a line on an existing plot. The general form of the command is: abline(a = intercept, b = slope).

qqp = qqplot(data$Total.Cases, data$Total.Deaths)
abline(lm(qqp$y ~ qqp$x))

#for normalized data
qqp = qqplot(data.norm, data.norm2)
abline(lm(qqp$y ~ qqp$x))

The basic method of applying a t-test is to compare two vectors of numeric data

t.test(data$Total.Cases, data$Total.Deaths)

## sample estimates:
## mean of x mean of y 
## 700174.34  12223.72

Two-sample t-Test with unequal variance:

t.test(data$Total.Cases,data$Total.Deaths)
## 
##  Welch Two Sample t-test
## 
## data:  data$Total.Cases and data$Total.Deaths
## t = 6.1311, df = 49.032, p-value = 1.466e-07
## alternative hypothesis: true difference in means is not equal to 0
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  462468.1 913433.1
## sample estimates:
## mean of x mean of y 
## 700174.34  12223.72

Two-sample t-Test with Equal variances: This can override the default and use the classic t-test by adding the var.equal = TRUE instruction, which forces the command to assume that the variance of the two samples is equal.

t.test(data$Total.Cases, data$Total.Deaths, var.equal = TRUE)
## 
##  Two Sample t-test
## 
## data:  data$Total.Cases and data$Total.Deaths
## t = 6.1311, df = 98, p-value = 1.836e-08
## alternative hypothesis: true difference in means is not equal to 0
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  465281.7 910619.6
## sample estimates:
## mean of x mean of y 
## 700174.34  12223.72

One sample t-Testing: In this version you supply the name of a single vector and the mean to compare it to (this defaults to 0):

t.test(data$Total.Cases, mu = 5)
## 
##  One Sample t-test
## 
## data:  data$Total.Cases
## t = 6.2411, df = 49, p-value = 9.937e-08
## alternative hypothesis: true mean is not equal to 5
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  474725.0 925623.6
## sample estimates:
## mean of x 
##  700174.3

Using Directional Hypotheses: In this the direction of the hypotheses can be specified.

t.test(data$Total.Cases, mu = 5, alternative = 'greater')
## 
##  One Sample t-test

v = as.matrix(x)

Two-Way ANOVA: In a basic one-way ANOVA you have one response variable and one predictor variable, but you may come across a situation in which you have more than one predictor variable, in such cases use two-way ANOVA.

data.aov = aov(Total.Cases ~ Total.Deaths + Population, data = data)
